Athene was so startled, she nearly dropped the picture of Stormygale she held loosely in one hand.  Both hands now shaking, she returned the portrait to the bedside table and tried to think logically.  She had to think <!--EZCODE UNDERLINE START--><span style="text-decoration:underline">clearly</span><!--EZCODE UNDERLINE END-->.  She had to act.  From where had Stormygale spoken?  Athene’s blood ran ice cold.  She had never known Stormygale to cry out in such a way.  Had she heard her ask for help—ever?  Maybe when her mother was ill, but the request had not been such as this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Where, Stormy?  Where?</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
The wind brought nothing more.<br>
<br>
Athene pulled herself up, unsteady on her feet.  I’ll got to get a grip on myself or I will be useless.  Consciously affecting a confident stride, she left Abruzi’s room and made her way to the kitchen.  She needed to leave, and she needed to act.  But where should she go?  Had she only been able to reach Stormygale because of some magic in the tree that bound them still?  Or was it simply that Stormygale had reached her end?  Athene had no idea, but remained where she was.  She had urged Stormygale to return to this place.  If Stormygale had heard, was she in a position to take action?  Athene had earlier sent a similar mind link out to Saphron as well—Saphron who had not answered.  A new worry.<br>
<br>
One day, I will know if I acted for good or nil, she said to herself.  Quickly, she set about making a fire in the main hall and in the kitchen.  She found blankets and set them by the fire to absorb its warmth.  She got no further when a sharp message stabbed into her mind.  <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>Kill me, please...please!</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--><br>
<br>
Athene began to pace.  Then she returned to action.  She hung a pot over the fire in the main hall, and from her packs she brought forth some rabbit meat and foraged vegetables and began to make a stew.<br>
<br>
A pounding on the door terrified her.  She was more skittish than she could remember being.  Steeling her nerves, she made for the door and swung it open.  Stormygale lay slumped on the ground.  The air around her shimmered and evanesced.  Some summoned creature had returned to an astral plane.  <br>
