<br>
“Nothing, but a wasteland of a half dead forest constantly being put to the test by the 3 factions that be always battling, and fighting thru this wasteland. A once beautiful forest filled with bright neon green leaves, grass, and brush turned into nothing more than a battlefield”, Revil sneers.<br>
<br>
The giants, puppets of Rallos Zek to help him fight the dragon horde that have been the long driving force in Norrath. The giants have no respect for their surroundings, but more of their goals to drive the dragon horde out of existence. Revil has no respect for the giant’s goals, but had no remorse tricking them into thinking he believed in their cause. Revil slowly looks at his pieces of rugged chain mail armor the giants made for him during his service.<br>
<br>
Dragonkin, the spawn of Veeshan. Keepers of the land that kept balance between the gods, and mortals of Norrath. Constantly being tested from all fronts by mortals for their nice loot they keep stashed for themselves, and by the gods to take them out of existence to have more power over Norrath as a whole. They are weary of any travelers who try to prove themselves, as they should be. <br>
<br>
Revil slowly gazes at the pieces of armor the dragonkin have made for him. Finely made chain mail almost as beautiful as mithril, and as strong as dragon scales. Revil chuckles as he turned on the dragons after he used them for personal gain, and manipulated them like puppets on a short string.<br>
<br>
The Tunarean Court. Followers, and leading force for the God of Nature, Tunare. Constantly battling the giants for their lack of care for the forest. That is the only Knowledge Revil took the time to research on the court seeing as he has no use for what the nature guardians could give him for his skills.<br>
<br>
Revil gathers himself, and makes his way across the wasteland to the home of the giants, Keal Drakkal. He can take a quick rest while restocking on supplies for the long journey ahead of him. As Revil sneaks across the wasteland he feels a slight glow of heat coming from his ankle pack. He stops dead in his tracks, frozen into a cautious pose scanning his surrounds for trouble before he slowly kneels down, and opens up his ankle pack.<br>
<br>
The glow is coming from the locket he got from that human girl. He slowly pulls the locket out to examine it for any changes. He feels around the back where the engraving of words are, and feels them slowly changing. A bit frightened, Revil drops the locket on the ground.<br>
<br>
“What type of witch craft is this nonsense”, as Revil watches the locket roll, and slide slightly down the hill.<br>
<br>
The glowing of the locket gets brighter, and brighter. Revil quickly rushes to pick it up so it doesn’t attract any unwanted lurkers. After picking up the locket, he put the locket back into his ankle pack, and makes great haste to Keal Drakkal where he can examine the locket better in more peace of mind, and figure out why this locket is glowing.<br>
<br>
As Revil runs to Keal Drakkal he mutters, &quot;Mabye, the locket is bound to that girl somehow. Just maybe...&quot; <p><!--EZCODE LINK START--><a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=172191" target="top">Revil Nemessis</a><!--EZCODE LINK END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->65th Shiza Riza of the Half-Breed Conspiracy<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END-->One pistol of a Rogue<!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--><!--EZCODE FONT START--><span style="color:red;"><!--EZCODE BOLD START--><strong>Disclaimer: Disgruntled for entertainment purposes only</strong><!--EZCODE BOLD END--></span><!--EZCODE FONT END--><!--EZCODE BR START--><br /><!--EZCODE BR END--></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#212128><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stormygalewindrunner>Stormygale Windrunner</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.cpmission.com/graphics/icons/icon45.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Member</span><br>  Posts: 896<br> <font color=#7A8798>(7/24/03 5:32 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=53>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> It was warm, and she was comfortable.  She awoke to that thought and did not move. She wondered, had she died? Was if finally over and that was why she didn't hurt? Ahhh, but she was hungry. So this was a dream? It must be because she still didn't hurt. But her hands, she realized, were shaking like leaves in the wind. This was no dream. Then why didn't she hurt?<br>
<br>
Stormygale opened her eyes and saw the flickerings of a fire burning on a hearth, and felt the warmth of it on her side.  She knew that hearth though. She'd known that hearth for more years than she could count. The smells and feelings of home invaded her and she was more than comfortable.  &quot;Mom?&quot; she asked, and fully expected her mother to be bustling somewhere near, but then reality set in as two sets of hands gently, yet firmly held her down, and the crush of her loss of her mother let them. What did it matter now?<br>
<br>
She turned her head to find Athene and Saphron hovering over her, looking apprehensive as if she were going to bolt again. She relaxed. She was too tired and too comfortalbe to move. <br>
<br>
&quot;Hello you two. So you caught me at last, eh? Well, I'm too tired to move. Have you got anything to eat and maybe a bit of my mother's brandy about?  My hands are shaking,&quot; and slowly she withdew one to show it trembling uncontrolably. &quot;Too much drink I think.&quot;  <p><b>Stormygale El`Orian</b><img border=0 src="http://www.cpmission.com/graphics/icons/icon45.gif" /></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=stormygalewindrunner>Stormygale Windrunner</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.cpmission.com/graphics/icons/icon45.gif" BORDER=0> at: 7/24/03 5:35 am<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#141419><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub148.ezboard.com/bthewordsofnagafen.showUserPublicProfile?gid=athene>Athene</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/_uimages/ahstarsm.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>CoN Member</span><br>  Posts: 89<br> <font color=#7A8798>(7/24/03 7:37 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub148.ezboard.com/fthewordsofnagafenmuirlansweeklypics.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=142.topic&index=54>Reply</a>    <br>ezSupporter<br> <BR><img src=http://home.mindspring.com/~abvogan/eye.JPG WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: The Fraud</span><hr size=1> Athene was ready with both requests—or nearly ready.  The stew would need to be scooped up and served hot.  She’d see about that later.  Alcohol was Stormygale’s most pressing need, and neither she nor Saphron felt their friend needed to eschew the stuff.  She’s never had a problem with it before this injury and this depression.  Not that Stormygale couldn’t slam back a significant amount of the good stuff.  She could and could keep up with the best of them, but the craving had come with the pain.<br>
<br>
Athene came forward with a glass, filled to three quarters.  “Apricot cooler.  Not as strong as what you’re gotten used to, but a good drink nonetheless—apricot brandy, lemon, lime, grenadine, sugar, and club soda.  It should help take the edge off.”  <br>
<br>
Stormygale seemed grateful or in some strange state of peace.  She didn’t protest as Athene set the glass on a table and Athene and Saphron began to help her first into a simple shift and then into a low chair by the fire.  Saphron insisted that Stormygale sit up straight while she placed pillows strategically around her to support her.  Seeming satisfied, Saphron stood back and surveyed her patient.  “Yer lookin’ better, but yer not well.  I can help stave off the pain, but the underlying causes are still there, and we’re going to have to deal with them.”  Saphron motioned for Athene to pass Stormygale her drink.<br>
<br>
Stormygale took it and sipped.  It was good.  She wondered briefly if she were under some sort of spell, for she didn’t have the slightest urge to defy Saphron.  Usually, just the sight of the halfling cleric, so serious, hands on hips, would have brought out a bit of devilment from Stormygale, but she was feeling too comfortable to muster a display of fire, so she simply nodded her agreement.  Her primary concern at the moment was her hands, which continued to shake.  Athene took the glass and set it on the small table that had been pulled close.  “That will pass soon, I think.  Probably as much a lack of wholesome food as too much drink.”<br>
<br>
As if on cue, Saphron turned to the pot bubbling over the fire and began to ladle out a small portion of stew into a stoneware bowl.  She set it down carefully on the small table and said, “It’s hot.  Finish your drink first and let it cool.  Athene, be a bringing over some fresh water as well please.”<br>
<br>
Athene left for the kitchen and brought back a pitcher of fresh rain water the guild collected in a cistern out back near a shady copse of trees.  In former days, the guild’s dark elves, ogres, and trolls had favored this approach to the hall. <br>
<br>
When Athene returned, she found Saphron now seated in a chair across from Stormygale speaking gently.  “I think I know something of the cause of the pain in your lower back.  When you’re feeling a bit better and can stand a more thorough examination, we’ll know more.”  Saphron paused and continued.  Stormygale, whose hands now only revealed slight tremors, reached for her bowl of stew and began to eat very slowly.<br>
<br>
Saphron continued.  “Now, I don’t want you to be thinking I believe you too weak to stand the pain, Stormy, I don’t, but there’s nothing to be gained by aggravating the injury further and needlessly.”<br>
<br>
Stormygale listened.<br>
<br>
Athene poured three glasses of rain water.  She placed one within Stormygale’s reach and handed another to Saphron.  Athene drank her own in one swift draught and then sat on the floor near the cooling fire to listen to Saphron’s counsel.  “Your guild is worried.  Several search for you.  Athene has prepared a letter for delivery to Quaras, which will explain the current situation.  We have already sent  a message through the ether that you have been found.  I don’t know how long that news will take to reach all who search for you.  Athene and I think it’s best you continue your recuperation here.  It may be necessary, Stormygale, to reopen the wound in your back.  It could be that we will need to, in effect, re-break it.”  <br>
<br>
Stormygale took in this news without speaking.  Neither Saphron nor Athene could judge how she felt about such a possibility.  They had all suffered their share of injuries.  If this action led to a more complete recovery, it was likely Stormygale would accept it stoically.  The powers of Norrath’s clerics were limited somewhat.  Not every injury could be made completely whole.  Afflictions of the blood—diseases, poisons, most curses—could usually be cured.  The effects of these things and severe injury and age could not always be.  Athene, herself, had suffered years of residual pain from a stab wound to the back when Konaku had attacked her in the pass from South Karana to Lake Rathetear.  They had all seen men and women who had lost an eye or become blinded from their life’s adventures.<br>
<br>
Saphron set her glass on the floor.  “When you’re ready again for travel, Stormygale, you can make the journey home to the Claw.&quot;<br>
<br>
